Mississippi National Guard]]}}\n\n'''Ralph Lee Abraham, Jr.''' (born September 16, 1954)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://info.cqrollcall.com/rs/cqrc/images/CQNews_NewMemberGuide2014.pdf |title=Guide to the New Congress |publisher=[[Roll Call]] |accessdate=December 6, 2014}}</ref> is an American physician and former veterinarian from [[Mangham, Louisiana]], who won election on [[United States House of Representatives elections in Louisiana, 2014#District 5|December 6, 2014]], as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to represent {{ushr|LA|5}} in the [[United States House of Representatives]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myarklamiss.com/story/d/story/nela-doctor-running-for-congress/91351/n2Wcnu8DrkG-bKuzagMnNg |title=NELA Doctor Running for Congress |date=May 30, 2014 |accessdate=June 2, 2014 |work=myarklamiss.com}}</ref> He defeated his [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] opponent, [[Mayor]] [[Jamie Mayo]] of [[Monroe, Louisiana|Monroe]], by a margin of 134,612 votes (64.2 percent) to 75,004 (35.8 percent).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/12062014/12062014_23.html |title=Runoff election returns, December 6, 2014 |publisher=[[Louisiana Secretary of State]] |accessdate=December 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nAbraham is the son of the former Marlene Posey (1932\u20132015), a retired [[educator]], and Ralph Abraham, Sr. (1933\u20131980).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/local/2015/07/29/congressman-abrahams-mother-dies/30830519/ |title=Congressman Abraham\u2019s mother, 83, dies |author=Greg Hilburn |work=The Monroe News-Star |date=July 29, 2015 |accessdate=July 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAbraham has served in the [[United States Coast Guard Auxiliary]] and the [[Mississippi National Guard]]. He and his wife, Dianne, have three children. He is a graduate of [[Louisiana State University]] in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge]], Louisiana State University School of Veterinary Medicine, and the [[Louisiana State University School of Medicine]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Goddard|first1=Valerie|title=Is there a job Ralph Abraham can't do?|url=https://www.avma.org/News/JAVMANews/Pages/150801j.aspx|accessdate=October 29, 2016|agency=American Veterinary Medical Association|publisher=JAVMAnews|date=July 15, 2015}}</ref><ref name=newsstar>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/local/2014/11/22/abraham-remained-consistent-ersistent/19430723/ |title=Abraham: \u2018We remained consistent and persistent\u2019 |author=Greg Hilburn |date=November 22, 2014 |work= [[The News-Star|The Monroe News-Star]] |accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Tenure===\nAbraham was sworn into office in the [[114th United States Congress]] on January 3, 2015.\n\nAfter his election, Abraham announced that Luke J. Letlow, his campaign manager, would become his chief of staff.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/local/2014/12/10/letlow-named-abrahams-chief-staff/20201499/ |title=Letlow named Abraham\u2019s chief of staff |author=Greg Hilburn |date=December 10, 2014 |work=The Monroe News-Star |accessdate=December 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Nutrition|Subcommittee on Nutrition]]\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Environment|Subcommittee on Environment]]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Research and Technology|Subcommittee on Research and Technology]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Veterans' Affairs|Committee on Veterans' Affairs]]'''\n** [[United States House Veterans' Affairs Subcommittee on Disability Assistance and Memorial Affairs|Subcommittee on Disability Assistance and Memorial Affairs]] (Chair)\n** [[United States House Veterans' Affairs Subcommittee on Health|Subcommittee on Health]]\n\n==Political positions==\nAbraham believes the [[Affordable Care Act]] should be repealed. He opposes the expansion of [[Medicaid]]. Regarding [[illegal immigration]], Abraham opposes [[amnesty]] and supports strengthening border security. He supports simplifying the tax code, [[equal pay for women]], and approval of the Keystone XL Pipeline.<ref name=debate>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/politics/2014/11/20/mayo-abraham-face-th-district-debate/70035864/ |title=Mayo, Abraham face off in 5th District debate |author=Kaleb Causey |date=November 20, 2014 |work=The Monroe News-Star |accessdate=December 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Election of 2016==\n\nIn his bid for reelection in 2016, Abraham defeated one challenger, fellow Republican Billy Burkette<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/local/2016/11/08/abraham-reelected-5th-district-seat/93447078/|title=Abraham reelected in 5th district seat|last=Mott|first=Ashley|date=November 9, 2016|website=Monroe News Star|publisher=|access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> of [[Baton Rouge]], a former [[constable]] in [[East Feliciana Parish]] and a former chairman of the Louisiana Band of [[Choctaw]] Indians. Burkette claimed in his campaign that the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] has issued overly strict regulations that hamper [[farming]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewsstar.com/story/news/local/2016/11/05/incumbent-abraham-faces-burkette-5th-district-race/93288812/|title=Incumbent Abraham faces Burkette in 5th district race|author=Ashley Mott|date=November 5, 2016|publisher=''Monroe News-Star''|accessdate=November 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Portalbar|Louisiana|Politics|Medicine|Baptist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http:/